<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910926-0110</DOCNO><DOCID>910926-0110.</DOCID><HL>   IBM Is Granted   Approval by India   For Joint Venture   ----   By Eduardo Lachica   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>09/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   F GM IBM J.SUZ K</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)AUTOMOBILES (AUT)COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)SOFTWARE (SOF)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>JOINT VENTURES (JVN)TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><RE>FAR EAST (FE)INDIA (II)JAPAN (JA)MICHIGAN (MI)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A senior Indian trade official said hisgovernment has given International Business Machines Corp.the go-ahead to manufacture personal computers and softwarein that country in a joint venture with one of India'slargest industrial conglomerates.   Commerce Minister P. Chidambaram said that the Indiangovernment has approved IBM's application to produce PS/2personal computers and related software for both Indianconsumption and for export. The venture with India's TataGroup would mark IBM's first manufacturing activity in Indiasince the company was forced by restrictive investmentpolicies in 1977 to pull out of the country.</LP><TEXT>   The minister, who is in Washington leading a delegation ofIndian businessmen, also announced that his government hasapproved a joint venture between Ford Motor Co. and MarutiUdyog Ltd. to manufacture aluminum radiators in India.Maruti, itself a joint venture between the Indian governmentand Suzuki Motor Corp. of Japan, supplies economy vans andoffroad vehicles to the domestic market.   A Ford spokesman said the joint agreement could beconcluded within weeks. Ford declined to indicate the amountit may invest in the project.   The moves by India signal that the country intends to openmany of its industries to foreign investors after decades ofmostly unsuccessful central planning. Mr. Chidambaram saidNew Delhi will now allow foreign investors to take as much as51% of a joint venture in any of 34 designated industrialsectors. Only a few sensitive industries such as thoseconcerned with arms production or atomic energy will bereserved for Indian ownership, he said.   IBM had a fairly large manufacturing business in Indiauntil it was asked to sell 60% of it by the Indiangovernment. IBM offered an alternate plan for reducing itsownership, but New Delhi rejected it and the firm all butpulled out of the country.   Mr. Chidambaram said IBM will share equity in the ventureequally with Tata. An IBM spokesman acknowledged that thefirm had applied to launch the venture with Tata, but said ithad yet to receive formal notification that the plan wasapproved.   Mr. Chidambaram said his government is urging GeneralMotors Corp. and the Indian concern Hindustan Metals to speedup their plans to manufacture cars jointly in India. He saidKellogg Co. is involved in a joint venture to producebreakfast cereals in the country. He said the government isclose to approving the GM and Kellogg ventures.   A GM spokesman said the company hadn't yet received noticethat the Indian government had approved the company'sproposal.   A spokesman for Kellogg confirmed that the company wantsto build a plant in India. The spokesman said Kellogg plansin a few days to submit a final proposal to build a facilitythere.</TEXT></DOC>